    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_339176561" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/339176561" />
    <a title="Kelly" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2276205-kelly"><img alt="Kelly" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1285872916p2/2276205.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/339176561?book_show_action=true">May 29, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kelly" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kelly" href="/user/show/2276205-kelly">Kelly</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer339176561" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11186870222363691726">This book is hard to rate; I think I&apos;d give it about a 2.75. It held my attention throughout. It had a couple of moments that sent shivers down my spine. And I&apos;m not sure I won&apos;t read more in the Adelia series. But there are some technical issues with <i>Mistress of the Art of Death</i>, and more importantly, I feel like <i>Mistress</i> took me to darker places than I wanted to go, and didn&apos;t have enough of anything else to make it worth the trip.<br/><br/>Everything after this is a SPOILER. Also, this is not a formal </span>
  <span id="freeText11186870222363691726" style="display:none">This book is hard to rate; I think I'd give it about a 2.75. It held my attention throughout. It had a couple of moments that sent shivers down my spine. And I'm not sure I won't read more in the Adelia series. But there are some technical issues with <i>Mistress of the Art of Death</i>, and more importantly, I feel like <i>Mistress</i> took me to darker places than I wanted to go, and didn't have enough of anything else to make it worth the trip.<br /><br />Everything after this is a SPOILER. Also, this is not a formal review and not up to the standards I usually hold myself to. I'm typing it impromptu in the GR window, for what it's worth, rather than hashing it out in Word.<br /><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[<br />Technical issues: Mainly head-hopping. There are enough odd point-of-view shifts in the early scenes in particular, that I actually thought briefly that it was a paranormal and Adelia could read minds. Also, Adelia is forever noticing things and then not telling the reader till later. This is annoying.<br /><br />Darkness: This is a book about children being murdered in the most horrific of ways. And then some other innocent people are murdered as a result. An endearing animal character meets a nasty end and fulfills its foreshadowing in the most anticlimactic way imaginable. A minor thing compared to the child murders, probably, but it felt like insult to injury.<br /><br />Just...way into the heart of darkness here. And I read some pretty dark stuff, but in all my favorite "dark" books, there's something else to keep me going. More comic relief might have done it. A better romance might have done it. More scenes of human warmth might have done it--the dancing scene was a beautiful oasis in this sea of ick. Gyltha almost did it singlehandedly. But not quite. Cleverness could have done it--<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/9581507.Don_t_Breathe_a_Word" title="Don't Breathe a Word by Jennifer McMahon" rel="nofollow noopener">Don't Breathe a Word</a> is also about awful things happening to kids, but the plot is so diabolically genius that some of your focus goes to that instead.<br /><br />Romance--for pete's sake, Adelia, why didn't you just marry him? You could have actually <i>communicated</i> with him about why you were hesitant to marry. You could have negotiated with him--<i>sure, I'll marry you as long as I can keep practicing my profession.</i>. Anachronistic? Sure! But Adelia's already so anachronistic in so many ways (and I don't mean just by being a female doctor) that it's jarring when suddenly she can't be anachronistic enough to negotiate gender roles with the man she loves. Instead we get more drawn-out angst and then Adelia becomes exactly what she explicitly did not want to become: a bishop's mistress.<br /><br />But. But. The dancing scene was great. The scene where the river leads to Wandlebury Hill chilled me. So did the scene where Adelia notes that the convent looks and smells subtly <i>wrong</i> and then realizes why. <br /><br />Overall though, like I said, too far into darkness without enough to redeem it. <br /> <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span></span>
  <a data-text-id="11186870222363691726" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


