              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5480965-jackleen?shelf=1200s">1200s</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer203331871" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13120133885790301334">Four and a half stars.<br/>A historical thriller, The Mistress of the Art of Death, will rival modern day forensic medicine novels. The story combines medieval England in the 1200 century, crusader knights, questionable nuns, suspicious monks, and, a sly King Henry II, not to mention, four horribly mutilated dead children and the Jewish community that stands accused of these atrocities. The people of Cambridge believe the Jews have crucified their children in a passover rite. Then, add to this explos</span>
  <span id="freeText13120133885790301334" style="display:none">Four and a half stars.<br />A historical thriller, The Mistress of the Art of Death, will rival modern day forensic medicine novels. The story combines medieval England in the 1200 century, crusader knights, questionable nuns, suspicious monks, and, a sly King Henry II, not to mention, four horribly mutilated dead children and the Jewish community that stands accused of these atrocities. The people of Cambridge believe the Jews have crucified their children in a passover rite. Then, add to this explosive situation, the main character, Adelia, a woman Italian doctor, unusual in itself considering the times, who further specializes as a mistress of the art of death, the for runner to a pathologist or forensic medical examiner. An occupation not for the faint of heart. <br />Specializing in forensic anatomy, Adelia, works in this select area of medicine that is beyond most men, never mind a young woman, and excels. This chosen occupation is all well and good for Adelia, while working under the protection of the King of Sicily in the open minded cosmopolitan city of Salerno, a medical mecca of it's time. However, Adelia professional security is about to be altered in unforeseen ways. At the request of Henry II, who grieves for his lost income from his rich Jews, if not for the poor tortured children, The King of Sicily sends his best Master of the art of death, Adelia. However, Cambridge, England, is not forward in it's thinking, and Adelia must hide her talents, for fear of being taken as a witch. Joined in this espionage, is Simon of Naples, a top rate investigator and a Jew himself, sent to save the Jewish population of Cambridge, now holed up in the castle, in constant danger of attack from the town folk, outraged by the attacks on their children. The third party in this team is the Muslim eunuch, Mansur, Adelia's servant and protector, who becomes, to his surprise, the community doctor, to deflect the suspicions of the community from Adelia.<br />The three setup shop as a medical team, with Mansur as Doctor and Adelia as his assistant, while investigating the many potential murders found within the small town. The number of potential suspects is startling high, and includes prominent citizens of Cambridge, making caution the byword of Adelia, Mansur and Simon. As the three willow down the suspects, Sir Rowley Picot, a former Crusader knight, friendly and attractive, pops up unexpectedly and repeatedly at the sites of investigation, inducing both suspicion and unwanted feelings within Adelia. Rowley offers frequent aid and support within this difficult investigation and soon learns of Adelia'a secret skills. Questioning Roley's motives, Adelia, normally set apart from her colleagues in Salerno and even lonelier here in England, is confused about being attracted to a potential murder suspect.<br />Unexpected deaths and unexpected alliances add to the solid plot of a very good crime novel. Set within the historical backdrop of Cambridge, England and packed with many well sketched characters, The Mistress of the Art of Death is an Excellent who done it with class.<br />In addition, Ariana Franklin presents a vary valid reason for Henry II argument and subsequent murder of Archbishop Thomas of Canterbury that is both surprising yet so completely sensible that the reader can not help but have one of those light bulb moments so rare in literature.<br />The only detraction for this novel is the confusing number of characters that are thrust upon the reader within the first 30 pages. The initial flipping back and forth, to determine 'who is this again', cost Franklin the half star. But, reader be patient because once Franklin hits her stride in this book, you will be carried along in a surprisingly good top notch story. And, like all good detective stories, the ending is a complete surprise. So no peaking at the end. </span>
  <a data-text-id="13120133885790301334" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


